# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: asic-design-flow
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] An **application-specific integrated circuit** (**ASIC** /ˈeɪsɪk/) is an integrated circuit (IC) chip customized for a particular use, rather than intended for general-purpose use, such as a chip designed to run in a digital voice recorder or a high-efficiency video codec.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Application-specific standard product chips are intermediate between ASICs and industry standard integrated circuits like the 7400 series or the 4000 series.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] ASIC chips are typically fabricated using metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) technology, as MOS integrated circuit chips.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] As feature sizes have shrunk and chip design tools improved over the years, the maximum complexity (and hence functionality) possible in an ASIC has grown from 5,000 logic gates to over 100 million.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Modern ASICs often include entire microprocessors, memory blocks including ROM, RAM, EEPROM, flash memory and other large building blocks.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Such an ASIC is often termed a SoC (system-on-chip).
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Designers of digital ASICs often use a hardware description language (HDL), such as Verilog or VHDL, to describe the functionality of ASICs.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Field-programmable gate arrays (FPGA) are the modern-day technology improvement on breadboards, meaning that they are not made to be application-specific as opposed to ASICs.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Programmable logic blocks and programmable interconnects allow the same FPGA to be used in many different applications.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For smaller designs or lower production volumes, FPGAs may be more cost-effective than an ASIC design, even in production.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The non-recurring engineering (NRE) cost of an ASIC can run into the millions of dollars.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Therefore, device manufacturers typically prefer FPGAs for prototyping and devices with low production volume and ASICs for very large production volumes where NRE costs can be amortized across many devices.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] By 1967, Ferranti and Interdesign were manufacturing early bipolar gate arrays.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In 1967, Fairchild Semiconductor introduced the Micromatrix family of bipolar diode–transistor logic (DTL) and transistor–transistor logic (TTL) arrays.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) technology opened the door to the broad commercialization of gate arrays.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The first CMOS gate arrays were developed by Robert Lipp, in 1974 for International Microcircuits, Inc.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) standard-cell technology was introduced by Fairchild and Motorola, under the trade names Micromosaic and Polycell, in the 1970s.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This technology was later successfully commercialized by VLSI Technology (founded 1979) and LSI Logic (1981).
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] A successful commercial application of gate array circuitry was found in the low-end 8-bit ZX81 and ZX Spectrum personal computers, introduced in 1981 and 1982.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] These were used by Sinclair Research (UK) essentially as a low-cost I/O solution aimed at handling the computer's graphics.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Customization occurred by varying a metal interconnect mask.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Gate arrays had complexities of up to a few thousand gates; this is now called mid-scale integration.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Later versions became more generalized, with different base dies customized by both metal and polysilicon layers.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Some base dies also include random-access memory (RAM) elements.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In the mid-1980s, a designer would choose an ASIC manufacturer and implement their design using the design tools available from the manufacturer.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] While third-party design tools were available, there was not an effective link from the third-party design tools to the layout and actual semiconductor process performance characteristics of the various ASIC manufacturers.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Most designers used factory-specific tools to complete the implementation of their designs.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] A solution to this problem, which also yielded a much higher density device, was the implementation of standard cells.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Every ASIC manufacturer could create functional blocks with known electrical characteristics, such as propagation delay, capacitance and inductance, that could also be represented in third-party tools.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Standard-cell design is the utilization of these functional blocks to achieve very high gate density and good electrical performance.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Standard-cell design is intermediate between § Gate-array and semi-custom design and § Full-custom design in terms of its non-recurring engineering and recurring component costs as well as performance and speed of development (including time to market).
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] By the late 1990s, logic synthesis tools became available.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Such tools could compile HDL descriptions into a gate-level netlist.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Register-transfer level (RTL) design**: The design team constructs a description of an ASIC to achieve these goals using a hardware description language.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This process is similar to writing a computer program in a high-level language.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Functional verification**: Suitability for purpose is verified by functional verification.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This may include such techniques as logic simulation through test benches, formal verification, emulation, or creating and evaluating an equivalent pure software model, as in Simics.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Each verification technique has advantages and disadvantages, and most often several methods are used together for ASIC verification.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Unlike most FPGAs, ASICs cannot be reprogrammed once fabricated and therefore ASIC designs that are not completely correct are much more costly, increasing the need for full test coverage.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Logic synthesis**: Logic synthesis transforms the RTL design into a large collection called of lower-level constructs called standard cells.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] These constructs are taken from a standard-cell library consisting of pre-characterized collections of logic gates performing specific functions.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The standard cells are typically specific to the planned manufacturer of the ASIC.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The resulting collection of standard cells and the needed electrical connections between them is called a gate-level netlist.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Placement**: The gate-level netlist is next processed by a placement tool which places the standard cells onto a region of an integrated circuit die representing the final ASIC.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The placement tool attempts to find an optimized placement of the standard cells, subject to a variety of specified constraints.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Routing**: An electronics routing tool takes the physical placement of the standard cells and uses the netlist to create the electrical connections between them.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Since the search space is large, this process will produce a "sufficient" rather than "globally optimal" solution.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The output is a file which can be used to create a set of photomasks enabling a semiconductor fabrication facility, commonly called a "fab" or "foundry" to manufacture physical integrated circuits.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Placement and routing are closely interrelated and are collectively called place and route in electronics design.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] While Logic synthesis, Placement, and Routing are supported by electronic design automation tools, these stages require significant designer guidance and iteration.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Designers provide constraints derived from requirements engineering and RTL design, including timing requirements, floorplans, power budgets, and area restrictions.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Multiple tool iterations are typically necessary to meet performance, power, and area objectives, often requiring manual optimization and refinement that extends design cycle time considerably.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Sign-off**: Given the final layout, circuit extraction computes the parasitic resistances and capacitances.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In the case of a digital circuit, this will then be further mapped into delay information from which the circuit performance can be estimated, usually by static timing analysis.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This, and other final tests such as design rule checking and power analysis collectively called signoff are intended to ensure that the device will function correctly over all extremes of the process, voltage and temperature.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] When this testing is complete the photomask information is released for chip fabrication.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] These steps, implemented with a level of skill common in the industry, almost always produce a final device that correctly implements the original design, unless flaws are later introduced by the physical fabrication process.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The design steps also called design flow, are common to standard product design.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The significant difference is that standard-cell design uses the manufacturer's cell libraries that have been used in potentially hundreds of other design implementations and therefore are of much lower risk than a full custom design.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Standard cells produce a design density that is cost-effective, and they can also integrate IP cores and static random-access memory (SRAM) effectively, unlike gate arrays.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Gate array design is a manufacturing method in which diffused layers, each consisting of transistors and other active devices, are predefined and electronics wafers containing such devices are "held in stock" or unconnected prior to the metallization stage of the fabrication process.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The physical design process defines the interconnections of these layers for the final device.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For most ASIC manufacturers, this consists of between two and nine metal layers with each layer running perpendicular to the one below it.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Non-recurring engineering costs are much lower than full custom designs, as photolithographic masks are required only for the metal layers.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Production cycles are much shorter, as metallization is a comparatively quick process; thereby accelerating time to market.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Gate-array ASICs are always a compromise between rapid design and performance as mapping a given design onto what a manufacturer held as a stock wafer never gives 100% circuit utilization.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Often difficulties in routing the interconnect require migration onto a larger array device with a consequent increase in the piece part price.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] These difficulties are often a result of the layout EDA software used to develop the interconnect.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Pure, logic-only gate-array design is rarely implemented by circuit designers today, having been almost entirely replaced by field-programmable devices.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The most prominent of such devices are field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs) which can be programmed by the user and thus offer minimal tooling charges, non-recurring engineering, only marginally increased piece part cost, and comparable performance.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Today, gate arrays are evolving into structured ASICs that consist of a large IP core like a CPU, digital signal processor units, peripherals, standard interfaces, integrated memories, SRAM, and a block of reconfigurable, uncommitted logic.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In their frequent usages in the field, the terms "gate array" and "semi-custom" are synonymous when referring to ASICs.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Process engineers more commonly use the term "semi-custom", while "gate-array" is more commonly used by logic (or gate-level) designers.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] By contrast, full-custom ASIC design defines all the photolithographic layers of the device.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Full-custom design is used for both ASIC design and for standard product design.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The benefits of full-custom design include reduced area (and therefore recurring component cost), performance improvements, and also the ability to integrate analog components and other pre-designed—and thus fully verified—components, such as microprocessor cores, that form a system on a chip.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The disadvantages of full-custom design can include increased manufacturing and design time, increased non-recurring engineering costs, more complexity in the computer-aided design (CAD) and electronic design automation systems, and a much higher skill requirement on the part of the design team.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For digital-only designs, however, "standard-cell" cell libraries, together with modern CAD systems, can offer considerable performance/cost benefits with low risk.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Automated layout tools are quick and easy to use and also offer the possibility to "hand-tweak" or manually optimize any performance-limiting aspect of the design.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This is designed by using basic logic gates, circuits or layout specially for a design.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This is effectively the same definition as a gate array.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] What distinguishes a structured ASIC from a gate array is that in a gate array, the predefined metal layers serve to make manufacturing turnaround faster.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In a structured ASIC, the use of predefined metallization is primarily to reduce cost of the mask sets as well as making the design cycle time significantly shorter.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For example, in a cell-based or gate-array design the user must often design power, clock, and test structures themselves.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] By contrast, these are predefined in most structured ASICs and therefore can save time and expense for the designer compared to gate-array based designs.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Likewise, the design tools used for structured ASIC can be substantially lower cost and easier (faster) to use than cell-based tools, because they do not have to perform all the functions that cell-based tools do.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In some cases, the structured ASIC vendor requires customized tools for their device (e.g., custom physical synthesis) be used, also allowing for the design to be brought into manufacturing more quickly.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Cell libraries of logical primitives are usually provided by the device manufacturer as part of the service.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Although they will incur no additional cost, their release will be covered by the terms of a non-disclosure agreement (NDA) and they will be regarded as intellectual property by the manufacturer.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Usually, their physical design will be pre-defined so they could be termed "hard macros".
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] What most engineers understand as "intellectual property" are IP cores, designs purchased from a third-party as sub-components of a larger ASIC.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] They may be provided in the form of a hardware description language (often termed a "soft macro"), or as a fully routed design that could be printed directly onto an ASIC's mask (often termed a "hard macro").
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Many organizations now sell such pre-designed cores – CPUs, Ethernet, USB or telephone interfaces – and larger organizations may have an entire department or division to produce cores for the rest of the organization.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The company ARM *only* sells IP cores, making it a fabless manufacturer.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Additionally, open-source hardware organizations such as OpenCores are collecting free IP cores, paralleling the open-source software movement in hardware design.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Soft macros are often process-independent (i.e. they can be fabricated on a wide range of manufacturing processes and different manufacturers).
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Hard macros are process-limited and usually further design effort must be invested to migrate (port) to a different process or manufacturer.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Some manufacturers and IC design houses offer multi-project wafer service (MPW) as a method of obtaining low cost prototypes.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Often called shuttles, these MPWs, containing several designs, run at regular, scheduled intervals on a "cut and go" basis, usually with limited liability on the part of the manufacturer.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The contract involves delivery of bare dies or the assembly and packaging of a handful of devices.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The service usually involves the supply of a physical design database (i.e. masking information or pattern generation (PG) tape).
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The manufacturer is often referred to as a "silicon foundry" due to the low involvement it has in the process.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] An **application-specific standard product** (**ASSP**) is an integrated circuit that implements a specific function that appeals to a wide market.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] As opposed to ASICs that combine a collection of functions and are designed by or for one customer, ASSPs are available as off-the-shelf components.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] ASSPs are used in all industries, from automotive to communications.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For example, two ICs that might or might not be considered ASICs are a controller chip for a PC and a chip for a modem.
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Both of these examples are specific to an application (which is typical of an ASIC) but are sold to many different system vendors (which is typical of standard parts).
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] ASICs such as these are sometimes called application-specific standard products (ASSPs).
[src:asic-design-flow/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Examples of ASSPs are encoding/decoding chip, Ethernet network interface controller chip and flash memory controller chip.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] The earliest electronic design automation is attributed to IBM with the documentation of its 700 series computers in the 1950s.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] IBM has developed one of the earliest computer-aided design (CAD) systems, known as Automated Logic Diagram (ALD), which was originally executed on the IBM 704 and 705 mainframe computers.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] The design process started with engineers manually drafting logic schematics, which were later transcribed onto standardized templates and converted into punch cards for digital processing.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] Although focused on mechanical geometry, General Motors’ DAC-1, built jointly with IBM, was among the earliest interactive, graphics-driven CAD systems and proved the practicality of screen-based editing for complex engineering data, an idea adopted by IC layout tools.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] Prior to the development of EDA, integrated circuits were designed by hand and manually laid out.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] Some advanced shops used geometric software to generate tapes for a Gerber photoplotter, responsible for generating a monochromatic exposure image, but even those copied digital recordings of mechanically drawn components.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] The process was fundamentally graphic, with the translation from electronics to graphics done manually; the best-known company from this era was Calma, whose GDSII format is still in use today.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] In the early 1970s, developers started to automate circuit design in addition to drafting and the first placement and routing tools were developed.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] Because of the Cold War, developments often occurred in near parallel.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] In the Western world, the proceedings of the IEEE and the Design Automation Conference catalogued the large majority of the developments of the time, and by 1973 a large bibliography was needed to keep track of developments in the field.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] In the Soviet Union, progress was largely described in a series of books, starting in 1975.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] Calma’s Graphic Design System (GDS, 1971) and its 32-bit successor GDSII (1978) let engineers digitise and edit full-chip layouts on minicomputers; the accompanying GDSII Stream file became the de-facto mask exchange standard and is still recognised in modern design flows.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] The next era began following the publication of "Introduction to VLSI Systems" by Carver Mead and Lynn Conway in 1980, and is considered the standard textbook for chip design.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] The result was an increase in the complexity of the chips that could be designed, with improved access to design verification tools that used logic simulation.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] The chips were easier to lay out and more likely to function correctly, since their designs could be simulated more thoroughly prior to construction.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] Although the languages and tools have evolved, this general approach of specifying the desired behavior in a textual programming language and letting the tools derive the detailed physical design remains the basis of digital IC design today.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] The earliest EDA tools were produced academically.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] One of the most famous was the "Berkeley VLSI Tools Tarball", a set of UNIX utilities used to design early VLSI systems.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] Widely used were the Espresso heuristic logic minimizer, responsible for circuit complexity reductions and Magic, a computer-aided design platform.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] Another crucial development was the formation of MOSIS, a consortium of universities and fabricators that developed an inexpensive way to train student chip designers by producing real integrated circuits.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] The basic concept was to use reliable, low-cost, relatively low-technology IC processes and pack a large number of projects per wafer, with several copies of chips from each project remaining preserved.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] Cooperating fabricators either donated the processed wafers or sold them at cost, as they saw the program as helpful to their own long-term growth.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] 1981 marked the beginning of EDA as an industry.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] For many years, the larger electronic companies, such as Hewlett-Packard, Tektronix and Intel, had pursued EDA internally, with managers and developers beginning to spin out of these companies to concentrate on EDA as a business.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] Daisy Systems, Mentor Graphics and Valid Logic Systems were all founded around this time and collectively referred to as DMV.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] Department of Defense additionally began funding of VHDL as a hardware description language.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] Within a few years, there were many companies specializing in EDA, each with a slightly different emphasis.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] The first trade show for EDA was held at the Design Automation Conference in 1984, and in 1986, Verilog, another popular high-level design language, was first introduced as a hardware description language by Gateway Design Automation.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] Simulators quickly followed these introductions, permitting direct simulation of chip designs and executable specifications.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] Within several years, back-ends were developed to perform logic synthesis.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] Current digital flows are extremely modular, with front ends producing standardized design descriptions that compile into invocations of units similar to cells without regard to their individual technology.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] Cells implement logic or other electronic functions via the utilisation of a particular integrated circuit technology.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] Fabricators generally provide libraries of components for their production processes, with simulation models that fit standard simulation tools.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] Most analog circuits are still designed in a manual fashion, requiring specialist knowledge that is unique to analog design (such as matching concepts).
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] Hence, analog EDA tools are far less modular, since many more functions are required, they interact more strongly and the components are, in general, less ideal.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] EDA for electronics has rapidly increased in importance with the continuous scaling of semiconductor technology.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] Some users are foundry operators, who operate the semiconductor fabrication facilities ("fabs") and additional individuals responsible for utilising the technology design-service companies who use EDA software to evaluate an incoming design for manufacturing readiness.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] EDA tools are also used for programming design functionality into FPGAs or field-programmable gate arrays, customisable integrated circuit designs.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] Synopsys announced a planned acquisition of Ansys in 2024, but Ansys remains an independent, publicly traded company until the deal closes (expected H1 2025).
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] Many EDA companies acquire small companies with software or other technology that can be adapted to their core business.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] This is happening due to a trend to place entire electronic systems on a single chip.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] Machine-learning methods are now applied at every major stage of the integrated-circuit design flow, from high-level synthesis through sign-off.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] Machine-learning shortens turnaround times and improves power, performance and area (PPA).
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] EDA vendors have since integrated similar optimization engines into production toolchains.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] The OpenROAD Project (Foundations and Realisation of Open, Accessible Design), launched under DARPA’s IDEA program, released a no-human-in-the-loop RTL-to-GDS flow that has successfully taped-out designs.
[src:asic-design-flow/electronic-design-automation] Conferences such as ORConf and the annual FOSSi Foundation roadmap sessions now dedicate substantial tracks to open-source EDA progress.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] IC design can be divided into the broad categories of digital and analog IC design.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Digital IC design is to produce components such as microprocessors, FPGAs, memories (RAM, ROM, and flash) and digital ASICs.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Digital design focuses on logical correctness, maximizing circuit density, and placing circuits so that clock and timing signals are routed efficiently.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Analog IC design also has specializations in power IC design and RF IC design.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Analog IC design is used in the design of op-amps, linear regulators, phase locked loops, oscillators and active filters.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Analog design is more concerned with the physics of the semiconductor devices, such as gain, matching, power dissipation, and resistance.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Fidelity of analog signal amplification and filtering is usually critical, and as a result, analog ICs use larger area active devices than digital designs and are usually less dense in circuitry.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] An average desktop computer chip, as of 2026, has over 20 billion transistors.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] The rules for what can and cannot be manufactured are also extremely complex.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Common IC processes of 2015 have more than 500 rules.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Furthermore, since the manufacturing process itself is not completely predictable, designers must account for its statistical nature.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] The complexity of modern IC design, as well as market pressure to produce designs rapidly, has led to the extensive use of tools in the IC design process, known as electronic design automation (EDA) tools.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] The design of some processors has become complicated enough to be difficult to fully test, and this has caused problems at large cloud providers.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] In short, designing an IC using EDA software consists of designing, testing, and verifying the instructions that the IC will carry out.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Integrated circuit design involves the creation of electronic components, such as transistors, resistors, capacitors and the interconnection of these components onto a piece of semiconductor, typically silicon.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] A method to isolate the individual components formed in the substrate is necessary since the substrate silicon is conductive and often forms an active region of the individual components.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] The two common methods are p-n junction isolation and dielectric isolation.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Attention must be given to power dissipation of transistors and interconnect resistances and current density of the interconnect, contacts and vias, since ICs contain very tiny devices compared to discrete components, where such concerns are less of an issue.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Electromigration in metallic interconnect and ESD damage to the tiny components are also of concern.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Focused ion beams may be used during chip development to establish new connections in a chip.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Roughly speaking, digital IC design can be divided into three parts.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Note that the second step, RTL design, is responsible for the chip doing the right thing.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] The third step, physical design, does not affect the functionality at all (if done correctly) but determines how fast the chip operates and how much it costs.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] A standard cell normally represents a single logic gate, a diode or simple logic components such as flip-flops, or logic gates with multiple inputs.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] The use of standard cells allows the chip's design to be split into logical and physical levels.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Standard cells allow chips to be designed and modified more quickly to respond to market demands, but this comes at the cost of lower transistor density in the chip and thus larger die sizes.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Foundries supply libraries of standard cells to fabless companies, for design purposes and to allow manufacturing of their designs using the foundry's facilities.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] A process design kit (PDK) may be provided by the foundry and it may include the standard cell library as well as the specifications of the cells, and tools to verify the fabless company's design against the design rules specified by the foundry as well as simulate it using the foundry's cells.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] PDKs may be provided under non-disclosure agreements.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Macros/macrocells/macro blocks, macrocell arrays and IP blocks have greater functionality than standard cells, and are used similarly.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Standard cells are usually placed following standard cell rows.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] The integrated circuit (IC) development process starts with defining product requirements, progresses through architectural definition, implementation, bringup and finally production.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] The various phases of the integrated circuit development process are described below.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Although the phases are presented here in a straightforward fashion, in reality, there is iteration and these steps may occur multiple times.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Before an architecture can be defined, some high-level product goals must be defined.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] The requirements are usually generated by a cross-functional team that addresses market opportunity, customer needs, feasibility, and much more.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] This phase should result in a product requirements document.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] The *architecture* defines the fundamental structure, goals and principles of the product.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] It defines high-level concepts and the intrinsic value proposition of the product.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Architecture teams take into account many variables and interface with many groups.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] People creating the architecture generally have a significant amount of experience dealing with systems in the area for which the architecture is being created.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] The work product of the architecture phase is an architectural specification.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] The micro-architecture is a step closer to the hardware.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] It implements the architecture and defines specific mechanisms and structures for achieving that implementation.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] The result of the micro-architecture phase is a micro-architecture specification that describes the methods used to implement the architecture.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] In the implementation phase, the design itself is created using the micro-architectural specification as the starting point.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] This involves low-level definition and partitioning, writing code, entering schematics and verification.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] This phase ends with a design reaching tapeout.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] After a design is created, taped-out and manufactured, actual hardware, 'first silicon', is received, which is taken into the lab where it goes through *bringup*.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Bringup is the process of powering, testing and characterizing the design in the lab.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Numerous tests are performed, starting from very simple tests such as ensuring that the device will power on, to much more complicated tests which try to stress the part in various ways.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] The result of the bringup phase is documentation of characterization data (how well the part performs to spec) and errata (unexpected behavior).
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Productization is the task of taking a design from engineering into mass production manufacturing.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Although a design may have successfully met the specifications of the product in the lab during the bringup phase, there are many challenges that product engineers face when trying to mass-produce those designs.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] The IC must be ramped up to production volumes with an acceptable yield.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] The goal of the productization phase is to reach mass production volumes at an acceptable cost.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Once a design is mature and has reached mass production, it must be sustained.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] The process must be continually monitored and problems dealt with quickly to avoid a significant impact on production volumes.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] The goal of sustaining is to maintain production volumes and continually reduce costs until the product reaches end of life.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] The initial chip design process begins with system-level design and microarchitecture planning.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Within IC design companies, management and often analytics will draft a proposal for a design team to start the design of a new chip to fit into an industry segment.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Upper-level designers will meet at this stage to decide how the chip will operate functionally.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] This step is where an IC's functionality and design are decided.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] For pure and new designs, the system design stage is where an instruction set and operation are planned out, and in most chips, existing instruction sets are modified for newer functionality.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Design at this stage often involves statements such as *encodes in the MP3 format* or *implements IEEE floating-point arithmetic*.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] At later stages in the design process, each of these innocent-looking statements expands to hundreds of pages of textual documentation.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Upon agreement of a system design, RTL designers then implement the functional models in a hardware description language like Verilog, SystemVerilog, or VHDL.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Using digital design components like adders, shifters, and state machines as well as computer architecture concepts like pipelining, superscalar execution, and branch prediction, RTL designers will break a functional description into hardware models of components on the chip working together.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Each of the simple statements described in the system design can easily turn into thousands of lines of RTL code, which is why it is extremely difficult to verify that the RTL will do the right thing in all the possible cases that the user may throw at it.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] To reduce the number of functionality bugs, a separate hardware verification group will take the RTL and design testbenches and systems to check that the RTL actually is performing the same steps under many different conditions, classified as the domain of functional verification.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Many techniques are used, none of them perfect but all of them useful – extensive logic simulation, formal methods, hardware emulation, lint-like code checking, code coverage, and so on.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Verification such as that done by emulators can be carried out in FPGAs or special processors, and emulation replaced simulation.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Simulation was initially done by simulating logic gates in chips, but later on, RTLs in chips were simulated instead.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Simulation is still used when creating analog chip designs.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Prototyping platforms are used to run software on prototypes of the chip design while it is under development using FPGAs but are slower to iterate on or modify and can't be used to visualize hardware signals as they would appear in the finished design.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] A tiny error here can make the whole chip useless, or worse.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] The famous Pentium FDIV bug caused the results of a division to be wrong by at most 61 parts per million, in cases that occurred very infrequently.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] No one even noticed it until the chip had been in production for months.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Yet Intel was forced to offer to replace, for free, every chip sold until they could fix the bug, at a cost of $475 million (US).
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] RTL is only a behavioral model of the actual functionality of what the chip is supposed to operate under.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] It has no link to a physical aspect of how the chip would operate in real life at the materials, physics, and electrical engineering side.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] For this reason, the next step in the IC design process, physical design stage, is to map the RTL into actual geometric representations of all electronic devices, such as capacitors, resistors, logic gates, and transistors that will go on the chip.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] The main steps of physical design are listed below.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] In practice, there is not a straightforward progression - considerable iteration is required to ensure all objectives are met simultaneously.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] This is a difficult problem in its own right, called design closure.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Before the advent of the microprocessor and software-based design tools, analog ICs were designed using hand calculations and process kit parts.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] These ICs were low complexity circuits, for example, op-amps, usually involving no more than ten transistors and few connections.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] An iterative trial-and-error process and "overengineering" of device size was often necessary to achieve a manufacturable IC.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Reuse of proven designs allowed progressively more complicated ICs to be built upon prior knowledge.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] When inexpensive computer processing became available in the 1970s, computer programs were written to simulate circuit designs with greater accuracy than was practical using hand calculation.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] The first circuit simulator designed specifically for ICs was called SPICE (Simulation Program with Integrated Circuits Emphasis), released in 1973.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Its successors still dominate the analog design market.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] These computerized circuit simulation tools enable greater IC design complexity than hand calculations can achieve, making the design of analog ASICs practical.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] As many functional constraints must be considered in analog design, manual design is still widespread today, in contrast to digital design which is highly automated, including automated routing and synthesis.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] As a result, modern design flows for analog circuits are characterized by two different design styles – top-down and bottom-up.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] The top-down design style makes use of optimization-based tools similar to conventional digital flows.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Bottom-up procedures re-use “expert knowledge” with the result of solutions previously conceived and captured in a procedural description, imitating an expert's decision.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] An example are cell generators, such as PCells.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] A challenge most critical to analog IC design involves the variability of the individual devices built on the semiconductor chip.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Unlike board-level circuit design, which permits the designer to select devices that have each been tested and binned according to value, the device values on an IC can vary widely in ways that are not under the control of the designer.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] For example, identically drawn IC resistors can vary ±20% and β (gain) of an integrated BJT can vary from 20 to 100.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] In the latest CMOS processes, β of vertical PNP transistors can even go below 1.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] To add to the design challenge, device properties often vary between each processed semiconductor wafer.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Device properties can even vary significantly across each individual IC due to doping gradients.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] The underlying cause of this variability is that many semiconductor devices are highly sensitive to uncontrollable random variances in the process.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] Slight changes to the amount of diffusion time, uneven doping levels, etc., can have large effects on device properties.
[src:asic-design-flow/integrated-circuit-design] The three largest companies selling electronic design automation tools are Synopsys, Cadence, and Mentor Graphics (now Siemens EDA).
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] With the MPC arrangement, one chip is a combination of several designs and this combined chip is then repeated all over the wafer during the manufacturing.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] The MPC arrangement typically produces a roughly equal number of chip designs per wafer.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] With the MPW arrangement, different chip designs are aggregated on a wafer, with perhaps a different number of designs/projects per wafer.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] This is made possible by novel mask-making and exposure systems in photolithography during IC manufacturing.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] MPW builds upon the older MPC procedures and enables more effective support for different phases and needs of manufacturing volumes of different designs/projects.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] MPW arrangement support education, research of new circuit architectures and structures, prototyping, and even small-volume production.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] Worldwide, several MPW services are available from companies, semiconductor foundries and from government-supported institutions.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] Originally both MPC and MPW arrangements were introduced for integrated circuit (IC) education and research; some MPC/MPW services/gateways are aimed for non-commercial use only.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] Currently MPC/MPW services are effectively used for system on a chip integration.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] Selecting the right service platform at the prototyping phase ensures gradual scaling up production via MPW services taking into account the rules of the selected service.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] MPC/MPW arrangements have also been applied to microelectromechanical systems (MEMS), integrated photonics like photonics fabrication including also other materials than silicon like InP, flexible electronics, microfluidics and even chiplets.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] A refinement of MPW is multi-layer mask (MLM) arrangement, where a limited number of masks (e.g.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] 4) are changed during manufacturing at exposure phase.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] The rest of the masks are the same from the chip to chip on the whole wafer.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] Typically MLM approach is used for one wafer batch (consisting of several wafers depending on the fabrication line) and for one customer.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] By using MLM it is possible to get larger devices (even up to wafer size) or larger number of dies and wafers up to few batches typically.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] MLM is a smooth continuation from MPW production volumes upwards and therefore this may support also small/mid size volume production.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] Not all foundries support MLM arrangements.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] Due to the complexity of the technologies available and the need to run MPC/MPWs smoothly, following the rules, timing of the designs and use of suggested design tools are critical for leveraging the benefits of MPC/MPW services.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] However every service provider has its own practicalities including design data, die sizes, design rules, device models, design tools used, ready IP blocks available and timing etc.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] Turn around times and cost of MPC and MPW services depend on the manufacturing technology and designs/prototypes are typically available as bare dies or as packaged devices.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] Deliveries are typically untested, but in most of the cases the quality of the manufacturing process is guaranteed by the measurement results of process control monitor(s) (PCM) or similar.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] CMC Microsystems is a not-for-profit organization in Canada accelerating research and innovation in advanced technologies.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] Founded in 1984, CMC lowers barriers to designing, manufacturing, and testing prototypes in microelectronics, photonics, quantum, MEMS, and packaging.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] CMC technology platforms such as the ESP (Electronic Sensor Platform) jumpstart R&D projects, enabling engineers and scientists to achieve results sooner and at a lower cost.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] Annually, more than 700 research teams from companies and 100 academic institutions around the world access CMC's services and turn more than 400 designs into prototypes through its global network of manufacturers.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] This support enables 400 industrial collaborations and 1,000 trained HQP to join industry each year, and these relationships assist in the translation of academic research into outcomes—publications, patents, and commercialization.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] Muse Semiconductor was founded in 2018 by former eSilicon employees.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] The company name "Muse" is an informal acronym for MPW University SErvice.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] Muse focuses on serving the MPW needs of microelectronics researchers.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] Muse supports all TSMC technologies and offers an MPW service with a minimum area of 1mm^2 for some technologies.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] Muse is a member of the TSMC University FinFET Program.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] The first well known MPC service was MOSIS (Metal Oxide Silicon Implementation Service), established by DARPA as a technical and human infrastructure for VLSI.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] MOSIS began in 1981 after Lynn Conway organized the first VLSI System Design Course at MIT in 1978 and the course produced 'multi-university, multi-project chip-design demonstration' delivering devices to the course participants in 1979.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] The designs for the MPC were gathered using ARPANET.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] The technical background additionally to education was to develop and research in a cost effective way new computer architectures without limitations of standard components.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] MOSIS primarily services commercial users with MPW arrangement.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] MOSIS has ended their University Support Program.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] With MOSIS, designs are submitted for fabrication using either open (i.e., non-proprietary) VLSI layout design rules or vendor proprietary rules.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] Designs are pooled into common lots and run through the fabrication process at foundries.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] The completed chips (packaged or bare dies) are returned to customers.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] The first international silicon IC MPC service NORCHIP was established among four nordic countries (Denmark, Finland, Norway and Sweden) 1981 delivering first chips 1982.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] It was funded by Nordic Industrial Fund and R&D financing organisations from each participating country.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] Targets were training and to enhance cooperation between research and industry specifically in areas of analog and digital signal processing and power management Integration.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] Parallel with NORCHIP organised by same nordic countries there was Nordic GaAs program NOGAP 1986-1989, which produced modelling techniques for GaAs IC devices, and demonstrators of high speed digital and RF/analog MMICs.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] From 1989 to 1995 nordic universities, research institutes and small companies have been participating in european EUROCHIP and from 1995 on wards in EUROPRACTICE.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] CMP a French company working since 1981 started MPC operation with NMOS offering but expanding offering to CMOS and various other technologies.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] CMP was also the first official pan-continental MPC/MPW operation having link to MOSIS among other MPW arrangements globally.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] CMPs services have included variety of technologies including multi-chip modules (MCMs) suitable for the packaging of chiplets.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] BERCHIP MPC activity starting in 1994 was organised in Latin America.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] Numerous MPW services have been launched since 1994 worldwide.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] Tiny Tapeout is a multi project chip service that lowers the barrier to entry to chip design by using open source tools and PDKs.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] To reduce the cost of tapeout, up to 512 analog and digital designs are connected via a power-gated multiplexer.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] As of 2026 supported PDKs are Skywater's SKY130, IHP's SG13G2 and Global Foundries' GF180mcu.
[src:asic-design-flow/multi-project-wafer-service] Tiny Tapeout schedules multiple tapeout opportunities per year.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] In electronic design, a **semiconductor intellectual property core** (**SIP core**), **IP core** or **IP block** is a reusable unit of logic, cell, or integrated circuit layout design that is the intellectual property of one party.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] IP cores can be licensed to another party or owned and used by a single party.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] The term comes from the licensing of the patent or source code copyright that exists in the design.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] Designers of system on chip (SoC), application-specific integrated circuits (ASIC) and systems of field-programmable gate array (FPGA) logic can use IP cores as building blocks.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] The licensing and use of IP cores in chip design came into common practice in the 1990s.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] There were many licensors and also many foundries competing on the market.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] In 2013, the most widely licensed IP cores were from Arm Holdings (43.2% market share), Synopsys Inc.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] (13.9% market share), Imagination Technologies (9% market share) and Cadence Design Systems (5.1% market share).
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] The use of an IP core in chip design is comparable to the use of a library for computer programming or a discrete integrated circuit component for printed circuit board design.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] Each is a reusable component of design logic with a defined interface and behavior that has been verified by its creator and is integrated into a larger design.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] IP cores are commonly offered as synthesizable RTL in a hardware description language such as Verilog or VHDL.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] These are analogous to low-level languages such as C in the field of computer programming.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] IP cores delivered to chip designers as RTL permit chip designers to modify designs at the functional level, though many IP vendors offer no warranty or support for modified designs.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] IP cores are also sometimes offered as generic gate-level netlists.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] The netlist is a Boolean-algebra representation of the IP's logical function implemented as generic gates or process-specific standard cells.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] An IP core implemented as generic gates can be compiled for any process technology.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] A gate-level netlist is analogous to an assembly code listing in the field of computer programming.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] A netlist gives the IP core vendor reasonable protection against reverse engineering.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] See also Integrated circuit layout design protection.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] Both netlist and synthesizable cores are called soft cores since both allow a synthesis, placement and routing (SPR) design flow.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] Hard cores (or hard macros) are analog or digital IP cores whose function cannot be significantly modified by chip designers.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] These are generally defined as a lower-level physical description that is specific to a particular process technology.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] Hard cores usually offer better predictability of chip timing performance and area for their particular technology.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] Analog and mixed-signal logic are generally distributed as hard cores.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] Hence, analog IP (SerDes, PLLs, DAC, ADC, PHYs, etc.) are provided to chip makers in transistor-layout format (such as GDSII).
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] Digital IP cores are sometimes offered in layout format as well.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] Low-level transistor layouts must obey the target foundry's process design rules.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] Therefore, hard cores delivered for one foundry's process cannot be easily ported to a different process or foundry.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] Merchant foundry operators (such as IBM, Fujitsu, Samsung, TI, etc.) offer various hard-macro IP functions built for their own foundry processes, helping to ensure customer lock-in.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] Many of the best known IP cores are soft microprocessor designs.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] Their instruction sets vary from small 8-bit processors, such as the 8051 and PIC, to 32-bit and 64-bit processors such as the ARM architectures or RISC-V architectures.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] Such processors form the "brains" of many embedded systems.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] They are usually RISC instruction sets rather than CISC instruction sets like x86 because less logic is required.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] Further, x86 leaders Intel and AMD heavily protect their processor designs' intellectual property and don't use this business model for their x86-64 lines of microprocessors.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] IP cores are also licensed for various peripheral controllers such as for PCI Express, SDRAM, Ethernet, LCD, AC'97 audio, IEEE 1394, AGP and USB.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] Many of those interfaces require both digital logic and analog IP cores to drive and receive high speed, high voltage, or high impedance signals outside of the chip.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] "Hardwired" (as opposed to software programmable soft microprocessors described above) digital logic IP cores are also licensed for fixed functions such as MP3 audio decode, 3D GPU, digital video encode/decode, and other DSP functions such as FFT, DCT, or Viterbi coding.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] IP core developers and licensors range in size from individuals to multi-billion-dollar corporations.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] Developers, as well as their chip-making customers, are located throughout the world.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] The silicon IP industry has had stable growth for many years.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] The earliest silicon IP companies that were established in the 1990s and 2000s included Virtual Chips, Sand Microelectronics (both acquired by Phoenix Technologies), Integrated Intellectual Property (I2P) (acquired by Lattice Semiconductor) and Ingot Systems (acquired by Virage Logic).
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] The silicon IP developed by these companies focused on standards such as PCI, USB, IEEE 1394 (Firewire), AGP and DDR3.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] In the recent times, the most successful silicon IP companies, often referred to as the *star IP*, include ARM Holdings and Synopsys.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] Gartner Group estimated the total value of sales related to silicon intellectual property at US $1.5 billion in 2005 with annual growth expected around 30%.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] IP hardening is a process to re-use proven designs and generate fast time-to-market, low-risk-in-fabrication solutions to provide intellectual property (IP) (or silicon intellectual property) of design cores.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] For example, a digital signal processor (DSP) is developed from soft cores of RTL format, and it can be targeted to various technologies or different foundries to yield different implementations.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] The process of IP hardening is from soft core to generate re-usable hard (hardware) cores.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] A main advantage of such hard IP is its predictable characteristics as the IP has been pre-implemented, while it offers flexibility of soft cores.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] It might come with a set of models for simulations for verification.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] Hardening soft IP involves evaluating the quality of the target technology, the design goals, and the chosen methodology.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] Hard IP has already been verified for use in a specific technology and application.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] For example, a hard core in GDSII format is considered 'clean' if it passes DRC (Design rule checking) and LVS (Layout Versus Schematic).
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] In other words, it meets all the manufacturing requirements set by the foundry.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] Since around 2000, OpenCores.org has offered various soft cores, mostly written in VHDL and Verilog.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] All of these cores are provided under free and open-source software-license such as GNU General Public License or BSD-like licenses.
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] Since 2010, initiatives such as RISC-V have caused a massive expansion in the number of IP cores available (almost 50 by 2019).
[src:asic-design-flow/semiconductor-intellectual-property-core] This has helped to increase collaboration in developing secure and efficient designs.
[src:asic-design-flow/tape-out] In electronics and photonics design, **tape-out** or **tapeout** is the final stage of the design process for integrated circuits or printed circuit boards before they are sent for manufacturing.
[src:asic-design-flow/tape-out] The tapeout is specifically the point at which the graphic for the photomask of the circuit is sent to the fabrication facility.
[src:asic-design-flow/tape-out] The name originates from the use of magnetic tape to send the data to the manufacturing facility.
[src:asic-design-flow/tape-out] The term *tapeout* currently is used to describe the creation of the photomask itself from the final approved electronic CAD file.
[src:asic-design-flow/tape-out] A modern integrated circuit has to go through a long and complex design process before it is ready for tape-out.
[src:asic-design-flow/tape-out] Many of the steps along the way use software tools collectively known as electronic design automation (EDA).
[src:asic-design-flow/tape-out] The design must then go through a series of verification steps collectively known as "signoff" before it can be taped-out.
[src:asic-design-flow/tape-out] Tape-out is usually a cause for celebration by everyone who worked on the project, followed by trepidation awaiting the first article, the first physical samples of a chip from the manufacturing facility (semiconductor foundry).
[src:asic-design-flow/tape-out] First tapeout is rarely the end of work for the design team.
[src:asic-design-flow/tape-out] Most chips will go through a series of iterations, called "spins", in which errors are detected and fixed after testing the first article.
[src:asic-design-flow/tape-out] The roots of the term can be traced back to the time when paper tape and later magnetic tape reels were loaded with the final electronic files used to create the photomask at the factory.
[src:asic-design-flow/tape-out] A synonym used at IBM is *RIT* (release interface tape).
[src:asic-design-flow/tape-out] IBM differentiates between *RIT-A* for the non-metallic structures and *RIT-B* for the metal layers.
[src:asic-design-flow/tape-out] A synonym used at Texas Instruments is PG (pattern generation).
